.TH GENG "1"

.SH NAME
.B geng.pl
- Gendered Generator

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ./geng.pl

.SH DESCRIPTION
geng.pl is a small program to automatically generate gendered variants for other tools, such as
.B kstfg.pl(1).

.SH HOW GENG WORKS
.P
geng.pl requires a strict directory structure due to some names being hardcoded. Consult
.B directory-structure(5)
for more info. In short, geng duplicates existing variant files and appends a "Male/Female" string to their name, appending the line
.B GENDER=MALE/FEMALE
to the variant's klof, as well as registering a gendered pair inside
.B greg(1)'s
.I tmp/java/registry/InitTransfurs.java
registry file, by expanding
.I ./*PERL_GENDERED*/
string into it's list 

.P
At first, geng evaluates files inside
.I tmp/klofs/variants/
directory.

.P
During this operation, geng reads through the
.B klof(5)
files, searching for
.B GENDERED=true
string. If that string is not found, geng doesn't do anything. Otherwise, it starts it's work. Note: Due to order
.B autocopy.sh(1)
executes commands, geng is runned before preset expansion, hence putting GENDERED=true in presets is largely pointless without editing
.B autocopy.sh(1)
first.

If the string
.RB GENDERED=true
is found, GenG immediately begins generation.

GenG begins it's generation by duplicating the original klof and appending strings
.B Male
and
.B Female
before file extension, and deleting the original file.
Then, GenG appends a
.B GENDER=
scalar to each file, with their respective gender.

Up next is a small edit of the
.B greg.pl(1)'s
Transfur variant registry file.
GenG begins by figuring out the variant names with uppercase only letters, and a possible, unique (but not always correct) name for variant pair, such as "DARK_LATEX_WOLFS", instead of a correct "DARK_LATEX_WOLVES".
This is a minor bug and will not be fixed.

Next, GenG uses that data to generate a valid registration call to
.I registerPair
method, defined inside 
.RB net.ltxprogrammer.changed.init.ChangedTransfurVariants.Gendered
static class, and pushes the saved line to a buffer.

Finally, once all files have been checked, GenG opens a
.I tmp/java/registry/InitTransfurs.java
file, and replaces
.B /*PERL_GENDERED*/
string with it's internal buffer, saved in previous step.
